article.headline: No. 10 Villanova tops Saint Joseph's 74-46
article.story: VILLANOVA, Pa. -- Darrun Hilliard put back his rebound for a layup and Daniel Ochefu followed with a bucket inside. Then it was time to mix up the offense. Josh Hart hit a 3, Kris Jenkins buried two straight 3s and Villanova's romp was in full swing. Stop the Wildcats? Sure, but which ones? This is a Big East favorite building momentum with a collection of go-to guys instead of one or two dominant scorers. Hart scored 12 points and Hilliard and Phil Booth each had 11 to lead No. 10 Villanova to a 74-46 win over Saint Joseph's on Saturday. The Wildcats (8-0) scored the first eight points, led by 15 only 6 minutes into the game and treated the rest of it like a glorified exhibition against one of their biggest rivals. Villanova thumped Saint Joseph's 98-68 last year and has remained the class of Philadelphia's six Division I teams. Without a true No. 1 scorer, the Wildcats continue to play solid team ball under coach Jay Wright. Up 25 in the second half, no Wildcat had hit double-digit scoring. Ryan Arcidiacono scored the first basket of the second half and became the ninth Wildcat to score. "I wouldn't say we have one guy that's super talented carrying the team," Wright said. "I think we've got eight guys that could carry the team." The Hawks (4-4) learned that lesson the hard way. The Wildcats had wins on consecutive nights last week against ranked teams Michigan and Virginia Commonwealth to earn the Legends Classic title. They thumped Delaware on Sunday and kept on rolling in a win Wednesday against La Salle. The Hawks were just the latest team to have no answer to a team that wants their first Final Four appearance since 2009. Ochefu and Hilliard opened the game with nearly identical right-handed layups. Hart hit a 3, Jenkins followed with two straight 3-pointers of his own and Ochefu brought down the house with a thunderous dunk for a 19-4 lead as Villanova quickly set the tempo. Hart scored 12 points on three baskets from the floor. "I feel comfortable when I'm open, or when they find me in transition," Hart said. The Hawks, who had 20 turnovers, were never comfortable in this one. Saint Joseph's missed 18 straight shots over 11 minutes, 49 seconds spanning the first and second half. Trailing 44-24 at halftime, the Hawks scored only four points in the first 10 minutes of the second half. The Hawks missed 21 of 22 shots in one stretch. DeAndre Bembry led the Hawks with 13 points. "It's a really, really hard game when the ball doesn't go in the basket," coach Phil Martelli said. "For us right now, it just doesn't go in the basket." The Wildcats have found their groove from 3-point range after a slow start behind the arc this season. They were 33 of 114 (29 percent) over the first five games, then made 20 of 46 (43 percent) in the last two games. Led by two each from Dylan Ennis and Jenkins, the Wildcats made 8 of 15 in the first half, the kind of long-range accuracy that ensured the Hawks could not rally. Villanova is only about 7 miles from Saint Joseph's and the Pavilion was filled with trash-talking chants from the student sections. TIP-INS Saint Joseph's: Freshman forward Jai Williams returned after sitting out the last five games because of oral surgery. ... Saint Joe's has not defeated a top-10 team since it knocked off No. 8 Xavier on March 6, 2008. ... Forward Isaiah Miles fouled out and was scoreless in only 9 total minutes. He scored 20 points last game against Temple. Villanova: The Wildcats have won eight straight games in the city series. ... No Wildcat has scored more than 20 points in a game this season. UGLY NUMBERS: It wasn't a perfect win for the Wildcats. They made only 13 of 24 free throws and were outrebounded 42-41. Villanova made a season-high 15 turnovers. HE SAID IT: "I got on the assistants at half because they're blasting away, blasting away, blasting away. That's not it. It's skills," Martelli said. UP NEXT Saint Joseph's: Hosts Loyola-Maryland on Tuesday. Villanova: Plays No. 24 Illinois on Tuesday at Madison Square Garden in the Jimmy V Classic.
